      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Liberal Endorsement</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jon D Michaels letters says Liberal Party's senatorial endorsement may help Mayor Rudolph W Giuliani, but voters should consider potential emptiness of such backing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Liberal Party's senatorial endorsement might help Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani (news article, May 7), but voters should consider the potential emptiness of such backing.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Liberal Party's senatorial endorsement might help Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani (news article, May 7), but voters should consider the potential emptiness of such backing.</p>
        <p>The Liberal Party's credibility is undermined by the intimate relationship of its leader, Raymond B. Harding, with Mr. Giuliani. Theirs is one of quid pro quo cronyism that has led Mr. Harding to give Mr. Giuliani his party's support in exchange for the mayor's well-publicized friendship, a friendship that bolstered Mr. Harding's lobbying business and resulted in high-ranking city appointments for Mr. Harding's sons.</p>
        <p>Such horse-trading is commonplace, but it challenges the integrity of this purportedly progressive party. Mr. Harding's support for the mayor, whose illiberal record on education and civil liberties is hardly debatable, should encourage voters to discount the merit and meaning of the Liberal endorsement.</p>
        <p>JON D. MICHAELS  Oxford, England, May 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
